   =20
      Bank M&A
   =20
 =20
One conclusion that a lot of people have drawn from the 2023 crisis of US r=
egional banks is that the US has way too many regional banks. There are mor=
e than 4,000 banks, which creates a lot of work for bank supervisors, and w=
hich means that it=E2=80=99s hard for depositors to be sure that their bank=
 is safe. When depositors get nervous, they run to household-name too-big-t=
o-fail banks, leaving the other, you know, 3,990 banks vulnerable.One obvio=
us solution to this problem is to turn those 4,000 banks into, say, 2,000 b=
anks, or maybe 20 banks. That would make life easier for regulators and sup=
ervisors =E2=80=94=C2=A0fewer banks to keep track of =E2=80=94=C2=A0and als=
o make each individual bank a bit bigger and more diversified and hopefully=
 more robust.One thing that means is that it=E2=80=99s a great time to be a=
 financial-institutions mergers-and-acquisitions banker? The Wall Street Jo=
urnal reports:The industry is poised to consolidate at a pace unseen in yea=
rs. If July=E2=80=99s earning announcements revive fears of fleeing deposit=
ors, the push to merge may turn urgent. Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen pre=
dicted that higher rates may lead to more deals; and bank regulators are si=
gnaling they are open to them.=E2=80=9CWe certainly don=E2=80=99t want over=
concentration and we=E2=80=99re pro-competition, but that doesn=E2=80=99t m=
ean no,=E2=80=9D Yellen said about mergers.=C2=A0Peter Orszag, the former O=
bama administration official and incoming CEO of Lazard has privately urged=
 Yellen and her staff to pave the way for more bank deals, people familiar =
with the matter said.There are more than 4,000 U.S. banks, and many are sta=
ring at eye-watering technology and regulatory costs. Those expenses, along=
 with today=E2=80=99s headaches such as fickle depositors and shaky real-es=
tate loans, threaten to squeeze the industry=E2=80=99s profits.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6Regulators have privately expressed a general willingness to include mer=
gers as part of the solution to instability in the banking system, people f=
amiliar with the matter said.=C2=A0If the 4,000 banks should be 2,000 banks=
, that means there need to be about 2,000 bank mergers? I suspect that if J=
anet Yellen could snap her fingers and reduce the 4,000 US banks to 2,000, =
she=E2=80=99d do it. And if Peter Orszag could get mandated on a small frac=
tion of those 2,000 bank deals that=E2=80=99s a nice year for his financial=
 institutions group.I suppose a lot of those deals will be pretty small and=
 not that lucrative for their advisers, but on the other hand my impression=
 is that bank M&A is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t want to say that it=E2=
=80=99s easy, exactly, but bank mergers have a tendency to happen over the =
course of a weekend, so you can do a lot of them pretty efficiently. It=E2=
=80=99s not so much a long courtship and a quest for cultural fit, it=E2=80=
=99s more like opening a data room on Friday and saying =E2=80=9Chey we got=
ta announce a deal before the open Monday.=E2=80=9D You invite in 20 bidder=
s, you pick the top bid, you tell the other 19 =E2=80=9Csorry it didn=E2=80=
=99t work out but we=E2=80=99ll have three more of these next Friday.=E2=80=
=9D If there are 2,000 bank deals coming, you can kind of set up an assembl=
y line.=C2=A0The other nice thing about this business, for an investment ba=
nk, is that it is sort of countercyclical. Higher interest rates are bad fo=
r, say, private-equity leveraged buyouts, but they are good for making regi=
onal banks nervous. As rates go up, M&A will be quiet in a lot of sectors, =
but it might get busier in banking.By the way, one way to tell this story g=
oes something like this:=09Traditionally, when the Fed raised interest rate=
s, banks did not really raise the rates they paid on deposits all that much=
. The =E2=80=9Cdeposit beta=E2=80=9D was low, because for various reasons (=
relationship strength, local monopolies, regulation) banks did not really n=
eed to compete with each other on rates to attract depositors.=09In the cur=
rent hiking cycle, however, regional banks=C2=A0do=C2=A0need to pay competi=
tive interest rates to keep deposits, and as rates go up they have to pay u=
p a lot and don=E2=80=99t make any money.=09The solution is to merge banks =
to reduce competition so they don=E2=80=99t have to pay competitive interes=
t rates so they can keep making money.I don=E2=80=99t think anyone would pu=
t the story quite that way, and you can understand why. (=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=
=99re pro-competition,=E2=80=9D says Yellen, and no banking or antitrust re=
gulator is going to go around saying =E2=80=9Cthere needs to be less bankin=
g competition so depositors don=E2=80=99t get paid market interest rates so=
 banks can keep making money.=E2=80=9D) But I think it=E2=80=99s true? The =
basic problem in banking is that competition is good but financial stabilit=
y is also good, and they are kind of at odds with each other.
