      Weird CEO pay
   =20
 =20
=E2=80=9CMeet the CEOs Who Pull In More Than $100 Million a Year,=E2=80=9D =
says  this Wall Street Journal headline, but that=E2=80=99s not quite right=
:The chief executives of Hertz, Peloton and Pinterest all earned more than =
$100 million in 2022, topping almost every CEO in the S&P 500 including App=
le=E2=80=99s Tim Cook, who made $99 million. Also on that list: The man who=
 runs CS Disco, a cloud-services provider that caters to attorneys and has =
a market capitalization of about $500 million.=C2=A0Sure okay the CS Disco =
guy =E2=80=9Creceived $500,000 in salary plus stock options valued at $109 =
million=E2=80=9D in 2022, but he =E2=80=9Cearned just under $1 million tota=
l in 2021, the year the company went public in late July.=E2=80=9D So he pu=
lls in $55 million a year, on average, over the last two years, not =E2=80=
=9Cmore than $100 million a year.=E2=80=9D But that $109 million 2022 optio=
ns grant is not an annual occurrence; that=E2=80=99s meant to tide him over=
 for a while. =E2=80=9CWe believe that an up-front, long-term option grant =
with performance-based vesting would be most motivating to Mr. Camara and w=
ould have a greater impact than an annual long-term incentive award,=E2=80=
=9D  said the company in 2022, when it asked shareholders to approve the gr=
ant. Getting a $109 million one-time equity award is not the same as earnin=
g $100 million a year.Also it=E2=80=99s not real money: The $109 million is=
 the calculated fair value of the options grant at the time it was awarded,=
 but it consists of a bunch of options to buy stock at a strike price of $3=
2 per share, and they only vest in tranches if the stock reaches a series o=
f milestone prices starting at $150 per share and going up to $900. The sto=
ck closed Monday at $8.40 per share. If he gets the stock to $900 per share=
, then the package will be worth something like $3.8 billion to him, but on=
 the other hand at $900 per share this will be a $50 billion company and he=
=E2=80=99ll be worth it. But the most likely value of this $109 million pay=
 package is zero dollars.=C2=A0Not all of the examples are like this, but a=
 lot are:At Hertz, Stephen Scherr=E2=80=99s total pay of $182 million inclu=
ded $3.4 million in salary and bonus. A further $178 million in restricted =
stock is structured to vest through 2026, much of it only if the company=E2=
=80=99s shares reach 90-day average price targets ranging up to nearly doub=
le its current share price.In its annual proxy statement, Hertz said two pr=
ice targets had already been met, meaning about $50 million in shares at re=
cent prices stand to vest if Scherr stays employed through 2026, in additio=
n to roughly $20 million that vested on Dec. 31. =E2=80=A6Peloton=E2=80=99s=
 Barry McCarthy started as CEO in February 2022, after stints as chief fina=
ncial officer at Spotify and Netflix. His $168 million pay package at Pelot=
on was almost entirely in stock options, which vest monthly over four years=
.=C2=A0If you=E2=80=99re the new CEO of a smallish company, your board migh=
t want to give you a pay package like this: At the beginning of your tenure=
, they give you a huge upfront package of options that only vest if you mak=
e the company a big company. These options have a high theoretical value no=
w, but you can=E2=80=99t cash them in: They only turn into real value if yo=
u succeed over the next few years. The board gives you a big long-term ince=
ntive up front, and then lets you get to work to achieve it. If it works yo=
u get rich; if it doesn=E2=80=99t work then you don=E2=80=99t. But the conv=
entions of accounting and reporting transform this into =E2=80=9C$100 milli=
on annual pay,=E2=80=9D and so you make the list of best-paid CEOs.And so e=
very year there are stories like =E2=80=9Chere are some surprising CEOs who=
 make the most money,=E2=80=9D but those surprising CEOs are rarely on the =
list=C2=A0twice. One big exception though:Stephen Schwarzman of private-equ=
ity giant Blackstone earned the biggest pay package overall, at $253 millio=
n. Blackstone, larger than many S&P 500 companies at a market capitalizatio=
n of more than $100 billion, has a corporate structure similar to dual shar=
e-class setups that until recently have kept other companies out of the ind=
ex.=C2=A0Yeah I mean he gets paid a lot.
 =20
   =20
      APEs
   =20
 =20
We have talked a lot=C2=A0about AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s A=
PEs. Briefly, AMC was a meme stock, and it took advantage of this status by=
 selling as much stock as it could to retail investors. Eventually it ran o=
ut of stock: It only had about 524 million authorized shares, and it sold a=
lmost all of them. So it asked shareholders to authorize more shares, but i=
t ran into a problem: To authorize more shares, it would need a majority of=
 all its outstanding shares to vote yes, and most of its (largely retail) s=
hareholders didn=E2=80=99t vote at all. So it couldn=E2=80=99t get more sha=
res, so it couldn=E2=80=99t sell more shares at irrational meme-stock price=
s.So it created   a new class of preferred stock, AMC Preferred Equity Unit=
s, or APEs. It did a quasi-stock-split, giving out one APE for each common =
share, and then sold a bunch of new APE units for cash, both in market offe=
rings and directly to a friendly hedge fund called Antara Capital. The APEs=
 had a   clever voting mechanism: They voted alongside the common stock on =
all corporate matters, and (unlike the common stock) they couldn=E2=80=99t =
just=C2=A0not vote. (APEs whose holders didn=E2=80=99t vote their shares we=
re treated as voting proportionally to how the APEs who did vote voted.) So=
, after issuing a bunch of APEs, AMC went to its shareholders again, asking=
 them to (1) authorize new shares and (2) convert the APEs into common stoc=
k. And because of the APEs=E2=80=99 voting mechanics, this time it worked.C=
ommon shareholders   sued,   though, arguing that this was too tricky, that=
 it was a way for the board to get around shareholder voting rights. After =
AMC, I should say, there was a brief vogue for these sorts of tricky prefer=
red-stock voting schemes, and they seem to have been   shut down pretty qui=
ckly, so I suppose the shareholders might have won. On the other hand, it s=
eemed to me that AMC was using the APEs to solve a genuine corporate proble=
m (it needed money, had a good opportunity to sell stock, and had retail sh=
areholders who didn=E2=80=99t vote), and it was hard to imagine a court kee=
ping the APEs in limbo forever. I kind of figured AMC would win in court. B=
ut it   cut a settlement with the shareholders, in which essentially the AP=
Es would convert into common stock at a bit less than a 1-for-1 ratio: Each=
 APE would become one share of new common stock, while each share of old co=
mmon stock will become about 1.13 shares. This seemed like rough justice to=
 me: AMC got most of what it wanted, but the common shareholders got a bit =
more of the company than the APEs did.But a few shareholders objected to th=
e settlement, and the Delaware judge in the case took them seriously. She c=
ommissioned a special master to look into the settlement; the special maste=
r  filed her report last month. And there was a hearing last week. It was i=
ntense. Basically AMC and the lawyers who sued it came in to defend the set=
tlement, and meme-stock investors came to object.   Bloomberg News reports:=
The proposed settlement would force investors to give up too much in exchan=
ge for too little, Ted Kittila of Halloran Farkas & Kittila LLP, an attorne=
y representing settlement objector Rose Izzo, told Delaware=E2=80=99s Chanc=
ery Court.The =E2=80=9Cgrossly unfair=E2=80=9D agreement gives AMC=E2=80=99=
s board a free pass for its bad behavior and sends the message that compani=
es can engage in illegal corporate engineering, then =E2=80=9Cjust kick out=
 additional shares to people and pay them off,=E2=80=9D according to Kittil=
a.=E2=80=9CWhy are people loud? Why are people upset? Why are people angry =
right now? Because they=E2=80=99re feeling like they=E2=80=99re not being h=
eard,=E2=80=9D he told Vice Chancellor Morgan T. Zurn. =E2=80=9CA group of =
stockholders saved a company that they believed was being destroyed by Wall=
 Street insiders. They were ultimately stabbed in the back by the very peop=
le they saved.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Zurn acknowledged the =E2=80=9Cfervent and=
 inspired AMC stockholders=E2=80=9D as she opened the hearing. =E2=80=9CI h=
ave heard what you have to say,=E2=80=9D she told the two who came to court=
 Thursday.And the  Wall Street Journal reports:John Barton, an Air Force ve=
teran who owns AMC shares, said during the first day of the hearing on Thur=
sday, =E2=80=9CI speak to you today hoping to represent the 3.8 million ind=
ividual investors that are about to find themselves at a loss, saving AMC a=
nd its theaters.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CMy fear is that the individual investors =
are going to be caught holding the bag, not making the money that the short=
s and AMC will during this conversion event,=E2=80=9D Barton said.=C2=A0Mea=
nwhile, part of the special master=E2=80=99s report is a legal analysis of =
the strength of the case against AMC. She is skeptical of the APEs, writing=
 that there is =E2=80=9Cevidence that Defendants [i.e., AMC] forced the Cer=
tificate Amendments through, with the APEs=E2=80=99 voting power and the An=
tara Transaction, to subvert the will of the common stockholders,=E2=80=9D =
and that =E2=80=9Cit appears possible, although far from certain, that Plai=
ntiffs could have prevailed because Defendants failed to prove a compelling=
 justification.=E2=80=9D But the lawsuit was risky and the settlement is re=
asonable.=C2=A0But another part of the report is just an account of the sha=
reholder objections:Most stockholders who objected to the Settlement, and w=
ho are listed on Appendix A, did so without substantive legal argument. =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Many stockholders voiced concerns about the supposed existence =
of synthetic AMC shares, Wall Street corruption, or dark pool trading.I don=
=E2=80=99t know! This seems like sort of the sad endgame of the meme-stock =
craze: Some people thought that by buying meme stocks they were fighting ba=
ck against Wall Street corruption and dealing a blow to naked short sellers=
. Meanwhile though AMC was looking at the people buying its meme stock and =
saying =E2=80=9Cwell okay if they want to buy this stock we=E2=80=99re gonn=
a do everything we can to sell as much of it as we can.=E2=80=9D If you thi=
nk that a shadowy cabal of Wall Street insiders are   naked short selling  =
 phantom shares in dark pools in order to destroy companies, you can persua=
de yourself that buying shares of those companies at irrational prices will=
 both strike a blow for justice and make you rich when the short sellers ar=
e exposed. But mostly what happens when you buy shares at irrational prices=
 is that then they go down.In  related news:Investors have spent almost $20=
0mn trading theoretically worthless shares in Bed Bath & Beyond since the h=
omewares retailer went bankrupt at the start of May, in the latest manifest=
ation of the meme stock craze. =E2=80=A6An average of 18mn of the company=
=E2=80=99s shares have changed hands each day on over-the-counter markets s=
ince then, according to Bloomberg data. Users of the Reddit website have be=
en sharing highly speculative theories about possible turnround plans for t=
he retailer. =E2=80=A6The original meme stock surge in January 2021 was roo=
ted in anti-establishment angst, with retail traders looking to destabilise=
 hedge funds betting against fan-favourite stocks. Sudden increases in dema=
nd caused =E2=80=9Cshort squeezes=E2=80=9D that turbocharged the share pric=
e rally as hedge funds scrambled to cover their positions, with Melvin Capi=
tal becoming the highest-profile casualty.Now, however, retail punters are =
betting against each other. =E2=80=9CThere are no institutions shorting Bed=
 Bath at 25 cents,=E2=80=9D Chukumba, at Loop Capital, said. =E2=80=9CThere=
=E2=80=99s no =E2=80=98man=E2=80=99 to stick it to any more.=E2=80=9D
 =20
   =20
      Elsewhere in authorized shares
   =20
 =20
WANdisco Plc is a UK software company that traded on the London Stock Excha=
nge until its shares were suspended in March for =E2=80=9Cpotentially fraud=
ulent irregularities,=E2=80=9D oops. It sought to raise=C2=A0 $30 million i=
n new equity in the hopes of fixing the irregularities and returning to tra=
ding, and  yesterday it announced that the fundraising was a success. Today=
 it announced a small hiccup, or rather an =E2=80=9CUpdate to Fundraise Tim=
etable=E2=80=9D:In working to complete the fundraise process, the Company h=
as encountered the requirement under Jersey law to seek further shareholder=
 approval to increase its authorised share capital in order to issue the Of=
fer Shares pursuant to the Fundraise. =C2=A0Completion of this step, as exp=
lained below, means settlement of the Fundraise and Admission are now expec=
ted to take place on 25 July 2023, subject to the passing of the necessary =
resolution by shareholders.Under the Company's Memorandum and pursuant to t=
he Companies (Jersey) Law 1991 as amended, the authorised share capital of =
the company is =C2=A310,000,000 divided into 100,000,000 Ordinary Shares of=
 =C2=A30.10 each. Following the Fundraise the Company's enlarged issued ord=
inary share capital would amount to 114,725,069 Ordinary Shares. If all Off=
er Shares were issued, this would exceed the Company's authorised share cap=
ital by 14,725,069 Ordinary Shares, rendering those excess Ordinary Shares =
invalid.Consequently, the Company proposes to increase its authorised share=
 capital limit set out in its Memorandum from =C2=A310,000,000 divided into=
 100,000,000 Ordinary Shares of =C2=A30.10 each to =C2=A330,000,000 divided=
 into 300,000,000 Ordinary Shares of =C2=A30.10 each. =C2=A0The Company wil=
l convene a general meeting for 10.00 a.m. on 24 July 2023 ("General Meetin=
g") at which a special resolution to effect the required increase to the Co=
mpany's authorised share capital and amend its Memorandum will be proposed =
(the "Resolution"). =C2=A0The Company's existing shareholder authorities do=
 not provide the directors of the Company with sufficient power to allot an=
d issue all the newly authorised Ordinary Shares. A Notice of General Meeti=
ng will be posted to shareholders later today.Oops! We talked above about t=
he complex machinations that AMC used to try to raise money by selling more=
 shares than it had authorized. But AMC only did all that because it=C2=A0n=
oticed=C2=A0that it had run out of authorized shares. WANdisco apparently f=
orgot.
