   =20
      Robot analysts
   =20
 =20
Here is Greg Jensen, the co-chief investment officer of Bridgewater Associa=
tes, on   large-language-model artificial intelligence:He sees Bridgewater =
building an ecosystem where the firm has a de facto army of high-quality AI=
 =E2=80=9Canalysts,=E2=80=9D all thinking about the economy and markets and=
 then testing these ideas. At the current cutting-edge of LLM tech, he says=
, the bots can ace certain internal Bridgewater tests better than most firs=
t-year investment analysts.And so, =E2=80=9Call of a sudden if you have an =
80th percentile investment associate, technologically, you have millions of=
 them at once,=E2=80=9D he said.I am dying to know which=C2=A0internal Brid=
gewater tests they were. I have mentioned   my model of Bridgewater before:=
=C2=A0One stylized model for thinking about Bridgewater is that it is run b=
y the computer with absolute logic and=C2=A0efficiency; in this model, the =
computer's main problem is keeping the 1,500 human employees busy so that t=
hey don't interfere with its perfect rationality.=C2=A0This model might pre=
dict that the computer would create=C2=A0a series of distractions for the h=
umans; the=C2=A0distractions would keep the humans busy,=C2=A0but if you ex=
amined them closely, there would be=C2=A0telltale signs that the intelligen=
ce that designed them was not completely human. "In an iPad app called 'Dot=
 Collector,' employees weigh in on the direction of conversations while the=
y are happening." "Any meeting of at least three people is expected to hold=
 at least one poll." "One former Bridgewater employee recalls debating with=
 other employees for as long as an hour whether a misused apostrophe in one=
 of Mr. Dalio=E2=80=99s research reports was intentional or not."=C2=A0Good=
 ones, computer!If you were a Bridgewater employee, which parts of your job=
 would you want to hand off to a large language model? The =E2=80=9Cthinkin=
g about the economy and markets=E2=80=9D parts, or the holding-a-poll-after=
-each-meeting and reading-Ray-Dalio-memos-as-holy-scripture parts? Possibly=
 in the future Bridgewater=E2=80=99s AI models will  ruthlessly critique ea=
ch others=E2=80=99 performance in meetings, freeing up the human investment=
 analysts to=C2=A0not=C2=A0do that.
 =20
   =20
      Robot lawyers
   =20
 =20
What percentile junior lawyer is   a large language model?Law firms are adv=
ertising for experts in artificial intelligence =E2=80=9Cmore than ever bef=
ore,=E2=80=9D says Chris Tart-Roberts, head of the legal technology practic=
e at Macfarlanes, describing a trend he says began about six months ago. =
=E2=80=A6The revolution in generative AI, machine learning that can make pr=
edictions, has accelerated the legal industry=E2=80=99s search for more eff=
ective technology. Many firms are now putting together teams to figure out =
how to use generative AI across all their practice areas even as ChatGPT, t=
he chatbot owned by OpenAI, becomes something to be feared as well as embra=
ced.=C2=A0Legal services are the most vulnerable to ChatGPT-style software,=
 according to a recent University of Pennsylvania study. That=E2=80=99s fue=
ling concerns AI could replace a significant chunk of junior lawyer drudger=
y. The widely-accessible technology is particularly suited to time-consumin=
g legal work, because of its ability to instantly analyze large documents, =
predict successful arguments based on past cases or create questions based =
on pre-defined criteria for a deposition.=C2=A0Really much of the work of a=
 lawyer is =E2=80=9Cpredict how a judge will rule in a future case by patte=
rn-matching how judges ruled in a bunch of previous cases=E2=80=9D; it does=
 seem very LLM-y.=C2=A0
