   =20
      Insider trading opportunities
   =20
 =20
We   talked on Monday about insider trading and working from home, and I wr=
ote:That said, there is one classic form of financial crime that I=C2=A0thi=
nk=C2=A0would have to be increased by work-from-home? That form of financia=
l crime is =E2=80=9Clooking at your girlfriend=E2=80=99s computer to see wh=
at high-stakes deals she is working on,=C2=A0and then insider trading on th=
em.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The counterpoint=C2=A0is that if you work from home you c=
an really only overhear inside information from the people who live with yo=
u: your spouse, your live-in partner, your=C2=A0roommates, your adult child=
ren who moved back in to save money while working in their first investment=
 banking job, etc. Whereas if you work from the office you have many more o=
pportunities. Aaron Brown emailed me:The biggest difference for me personal=
ly is not riding the express Metro North to Greenwich and back has cut me o=
ff from the constant opportunity to overhear actionable non-public informat=
ion. There are similar opportunities in elevators in investment banks and l=
aw firms.He clarified that he never actually traded on this information, th=
ough   my view is that trading on inside information that you overhear on a=
 train is probably=C2=A0legal, in the US. (Not in Europe.) Now that a lot o=
f people are back in the office in New York and Greenwich, this suggests a =
money-making idea, which I will not spell out further. Hoo boy is this not =
legal advice.
