   =20
      NFT Stuff
   =20
 =20
Apparently Justin Bieber was  not the world=E2=80=99s most discerning colle=
ctor of nonfungible tokens:As of this writing, the floor price for the Bore=
d Ape Yacht Club=E2=80=94that is, the price of the cheapest-available NFT l=
isted on a marketplace=E2=80=94is about 58.2 ETH, per data from NFT Price F=
loor, or about $69,800. On Monday, the floor price dipped below $60,000 for=
 the second time this month, but it ticked back upwards throughout the day =
on Tuesday. =E2=80=A6The price drop has also made some of the seven-figure =
Bored Ape purchases stand out even more in hindsight. One notable example i=
s musician Justin Bieber=E2=80=99s January purchase of an Ape for $1.3 mill=
ion (500 ETH)=E2=80=94a pickup that was deemed questionable at the time by =
crypto influencers who said that he overpaid for an Ape with very common tr=
aits.Honestly this is good, if you have to have collected Bored Apes this i=
s the way to have done it:=09Bieber has tons of money, from doing stuff tha=
t people find valuable in the real world, and he could blow $1.3 million of=
 it on an impulse purchase without feeling bad about it.=09He did=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0put a ton of research into which Bored Apes are =E2=80=9Cgood,=E2=80=
=9D to Bored Ape collectors; he just bought one. Imagine if he had, like, t=
aken a two-hour meeting with an NFT adviser who schooled him on the fine po=
ints of Bored Ape trait rarity! Surely avoiding that meeting was worth $1.3=
 million to Justin Bieber.=09Nobody stole his ape, suggesting that Bieber i=
s more careful and less gullible than   all other NFT-collecting celebritie=
s.=09Now it is down 95% and he, I am pretty sure, does not care.Every other=
 possible story of collecting Bored Apes is more embarrassing!
